pesticide.PPE: Mixers, loaders, applicators, and other handlers must wear long-sleeved shirts, long pants, shoes plus socks, chemical resistant gloves made out of the following: nitrile rubber ≥ 14 mils, neoprene rubber ≥ 14 mils, barrier laminate ≥ 14 mils, polyvinyl chloride (PVC) ≥ 14 mils, or viton ≥ 14 mils and chemical resistant headgear for overhead exposure. In addition to the above, for aerial applications, mixers and loaders must wear a NIOSH approved particulate filtering face piece with any R or P filter; OR a NIOSH approved powered air-purifying respirator with an HE filter.

Active_Ingredients.name: Acetamiprid
Active_Ingredients.mode_Of_Action: neonicotinoid insecticide which acts through contact and ingestion to control target insects.

Safety_Information.general_Info: FIRST AID: If swallowed, call a poison control center or doctor; if on skin or clothing, take off contaminated clothing and rinse skin for 15-20 minutes; if in eyes, hold eye open and rinse slowly and gently for 15-20 minutes; if inhaled, move person to fresh air and give artificial respiration if needed.
Safety_Information.if_In_Eyes: Hold eye open and rinse slowly and gently with water for 15-20 minutes. Remove contact lenses, if present, after the first 5 minutes, then continue rinsing. Call a poison control center or doctor for treatment advice.
Safety_Information.if_Swallowed: Immediately call a poison control center or doctor for treatment advice. Have person sip a glass of water if able to swallow. Do not induce vomiting unless told to do so by a poison control center or doctor. Do not give anything by mouth to an unconscious person.
Safety_Information.if_On_Skin: Take off contaminated clothing. Rinse skin immediately with plenty of water for 15-20 minutes. Call a poison control center or doctor for treatment advice.
Safety_Information.if_Inhaled: Move person to fresh air. If person is not breathing, call 911 or an ambulance, then give artificial respiration, preferably mouth-to-mouth, if possible. Call a poison control center or doctor for treatment advice.
Safety_Information.physician_Note: There is no specific antidote. All treatment should be based on observed signs and symptoms of distress in the patient.
